    "In this tutorial, we demonstrate how to estimate spatial metabolomics maps from spatial transcriptomics datasets using Compass [[Wagner et.al, 2021](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0092867421007005)]. These inferred metabolite fluxes can then be integrated into MetaChat to infer metabolic cell communication (MCC)."
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0a0cf93e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Compass is a flux-balance-analysis (FBA)–based computational framework designed to infer cellular metabolic states from single-cell RNA sequencing data. It translates gene-expression levels of metabolic-enzyme-coding genes into reaction penalty scores, builds a constraint-based model of the metabolic network, and solves a set of linear programs to compute a score for every reaction in each cell."
   ]
  },
  {

   "source": [
    ":::{note}\n",
    "When comparing two or more datasets, it is crucial to manually adjust the\n",
    "`baseline` parameter in `mc.pp.generate_adata_met_compass` to ensure that\n",
    "all datasets share the same baseline value. This guarantees the\n",
    "comparability of normalized metabolite intensities across datasets.\n",
    "\n",
    "A practical workflow is as follows:\n",
    "1. Run `generate_adata_met_compass` separately on each dataset without specifying `baseline`:\n",
    "   > adata_A, baseline_A = mc.pp.generate_adata_met_compass(\"dataset_A.tsv\")\n",
    "   > adata_B, baseline_B = mc.pp.generate_adata_met_compass(\"dataset_B.tsv\")\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Compare the two baseline values and choose the smaller one:\n",
    "   > common_baseline = min(baseline_A, baseline_B)\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Re-run the function for both datasets using the same `common_baseline`:\n",
    "   > adata_A, _ = mc.pp.generate_adata_met_compass(\"dataset_A.tsv\", baseline=common_baseline)\n",
    "   > adata_B, _ = mc.pp.generate_adata_met_compass(\"dataset_B.tsv\", baseline=common_baseline)\n",
    "\n",
    "This ensures that the processed metabolite matrices are on the same\n",
    "normalization scale and directly comparable across conditions.\n",
    ":::"
